&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence from the Criminal Cases Review Commission[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Executive summary[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1
[normal]              
[normal]The Criminal Case Review Commission is the statutory body created in 1997 to investigate alleged miscarriages of justice and refer appropriate cases 
[normal]to the appeal courts
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]              
[normal]It has so far reviewed over 15,000 case
[normal]s
[normal] and referred more than 540 for appeal. The majority of those referrals 
[normal]were in
[normal] 
[normal]relation to the most serious crimes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]Thanks to determined efforts to make ourselves accessible to 
[normal]all who might need us, 
[normal]applications to the Commission have
[normal] risen by more than 50% sin
[normal]ce 2012. In spite of the increased workload, we have 
[normal]kept
[normal] performance at or around 2012 levels. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4
[normal]              
[normal]Our
[normal] real terms
[normal] funding shrank by almost 23% between 2008/9 and 2012/13. As a result there were redundancies and other cost saving measures. In 2013/14, in response to increased application rates, we received a small funding increase and recruited to cope with 
[normal]the 
[normal]increased workload.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5
[normal]              
[normal]The Commission 
[normal]long
[normal] argued 
[normal]that 
[normal]its powers to obtain information should cover the private as well as 
[normal]the 
[normal]public sector
[normal], as in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal]. 
[normal]The issue becomes more pressing as more functions transfer f
[normal]rom
[normal] the public to the private sector, but progress remains painfully slow.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6
[normal]              
[normal]Between April and November 2013
[normal], 
[normal]we
[normal] referred 24 case
[normal]s. This looks set to return the
[normal] referral rate to around 3.5% (the long term average) after two years when 
[normal]it
[normal] dropped below 3%.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7
[normal]              
[normal]We have
[normal] 
[normal]been concerned about a new series 
[normal]of cases involving 
[normal]the wrongful conviction of people arriving
[normal] in
[normal] the 
[normal]UK
[normal] as refugees and asylum seekers
[normal], or as victims of human trafficking
[normal]. These have become
[normal] a significant feature of our work.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8
[normal]              
[normal]In 2012 the Ministry of Justice 
[normal](MoJ) 
[normal]conducted its first Triennial Review of the Commission and
[normal] passed 
[normal]it 
[normal]with flying colours.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;[bold]9
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]Criminal Cases Review Commission 
[normal]is 
[normal]the 
[normal]statutory body 
[normal]responsible for investigating
[normal] alleged miscarriages of 
[normal]justice
[normal] and 
[normal]refer
[normal]ring appropriate
[normal] 
[normal]convictions
[normal] 
[normal]and/or
[normal] sentences
[normal] to the appeal courts
[normal]. 
[normal]It was established on 1 
[normal]January
[normal] 1997 by the Criminal Appeal 
[normal]Act
[normal] 1995. 
[normal]It was 
[normal]the first
[normal] body of its kind in the world.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10
[normal]              
[normal]To date
[normal], the Commission has reviewed more than 15,000 cases and has referred 
[normal]540
[normal] 
[normal]for appeal
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The overwhelming majority of
[normal] cases dealt with 
[normal]are of the most serious 
[normal]type 
[normal]– murder, rape, terrorism
[normal], drugs
[normal] and 
[normal]robbery.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11
[normal]              
[normal]Given the scope of its role, the volume and range of its casework, and its concern with 
[normal]the 
[normal]whole process from investigation
[normal] and 
[normal]prosecution
[normal] to 
[normal]conviction and sentencing, the Commission is uniquely 
[normal]placed to
[normal] comment on all aspects of the criminal justice system and 
[normal]can offer unparalleled 
[normal]insight into 
[normal]the 
[normal]causes of 
[normal]wrongful convictions as well as into t
[normal]he ingredients which make for safe, successful convictions
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]he Commission c
[normal]an assist others, not only 
[normal]in terms of 
[normal]the
[normal] prevention of unsafe convictions
[normal], but also in 
[normal]improving the system’s ability to build successful c
[normal]ases and ensure safe convictions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13
[normal]              
[normal]It is 
[normal]essential that the Commission is
[normal] independent of 
[normal]the 
[normal]executive and the judiciary because prosecutions are brought by the state, because a Commission 
[normal]referral
[normal] compels the appeal courts to hear the case and because it is sometimes the courts that are at fault.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14
[normal]              
[normal]Only if we are truly independent can we promote public confidence in the judicial system.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]15
[normal]              
[normal]In addition to reviewing possible miscarriages of justice, the Commission can
[normal] also
[normal] be 
[normal]asked
[normal] by the Court of Appeal 
[normal]Criminal Division 
[normal]to investigate and report on matters 
[normal]relating to live proceedings
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]16
[normal]              
[normal]Commissioners and staff are drawn from a 
[normal]diversity
[normal] of 
[normal]backgrounds including the legal profession
[normal], 
[normal]forensic 
[normal]scien
[normal]ces
[normal], 
[normal]law enforcement
[normal], journal
[normal]ism
[normal], acade
[normal]mia
[normal] and 
[normal]others.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]17
[normal]              
[normal]As of 2
[normal] 
[normal]January 2014, there are 
[normal]eleven
[normal] 
[normal]Commissioners appointed by the Queen on the recomm
[normal]endation of the Prime Minister and 
[normal]94
[normal] 
[normal]staff (
[normal]87.57
[normal] 
[normal]full 
[normal]time equivalent) based at offices in 
[normal]Birmingham
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]18
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]Commission
[normal] is 
[normal]operating
[normal] with a 
[normal]fiscal 
[normal]DEL
[normal] budget of 
[normal]£5,178,000
[normal] funded through grant in aid from the 
[normal]MoJ
[normal].
