[normal]Legislation[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]28
[normal]              
[normal]The Commission
[normal]’s 
[normal]power
[normal] under section 17 of the Criminal Appeal Act 1995 to secure material from public bodies
[normal] 
[normal]is
[normal] a key investigative tool.
[normal] 
[normal]There is
[normal] no corresponding power in respect of private bodies or persons
[normal] and
[normal] the absence of such a power 
[normal]i
[normal]nhibit
[normal]s
[normal] our work. A
[normal]t best, the protracted negotiations to obtain 
[normal]private sector 
[normal]material can delay a review by months, 
[normal]and at worst 
[normal]our inability to obtain information could
[normal] mean a
[normal]n
[normal] 
[normal]issue
[normal] remains unresolved and a miscarriage of justice 
[normal]perpetuated
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]29
[normal]              
[normal]The problem is becoming more acute as 
[normal]responsibility for material once held by public bodies is
[normal] increasingly e
[normal]ntrusted to private sector bodies.
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]30
[normal]              
[normal]In 2006 a
[normal]n inter
[normal]-
[normal]departmental working party 
[normal]concluded
[normal] that
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]Commission
[normal] should have the ability, under judicial oversight, to require 
[normal]the disclosure of material by private bodies and individuals
[normal] as is the case with the Scottish CCRC
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]Disappointingly, 
[normal]a
[normal]lthough action has been supported 
[normal]in principle 
[normal]by Ministers
[normal], and 
[normal]in spite
[normal] of the fact that there
[normal] 
[normal]have
[normal] been some twenty pieces of criminal justice 
[normal]related legislation since then, no 
[normal]appropriate 
[normal]statutory
[normal] vehicle has apparently presented itself to remedy this 
[normal]defect.
