[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Casework themes[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]41
[normal]              
[normal]We have recently seen some new strains of miscarriage of justice arising alongside the disappointingly familiar ones such as those caused by the non-disclosure of material that could have been useful to the defence, investigative tunnel vision, failure to make adequate background checks on witness
[normal]es and complainants 
[normal]and changes in the medical or scientific understanding of evidence. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]42
[normal]              
[normal]The most significant new strain of cases has involved refugees or asylum seekers. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Case[bold]s[bold] involving immigration-type offences[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]43
[normal]              
[normal]Over the last few years, 
[normal]we have
[normal] identified a series of cases where refugees or asylum seekers have been prosecuted for offences relating to their entry into the 
[normal]UK
[normal], such as having a false passport, having no passport or attempting to obtain services by deception.
[normal] The Commission is concerned about 
[normal]those 
[normal]cases 
[normal]where the
[normal]re ha
[normal]s
[normal] been a failure to deploy available
[normal] defences
[normal] 
[normal]which are designed to prote
[normal]ct people escaping persecution.
[normal] In a number of cases individuals have been prosecuted and advised to plead guilty when a statutory defence was available.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]44
[normal]              
[normal]We have raise
[normal]d
[normal] awareness of the issues with charities and other
[normal] organisations
[normal] 
[normal]working
[normal] 
[normal]with 
[normal]people
[normal] who may be wrongly convicted
[normal] in this way
[normal]. We have also
[normal] raised
[normal] awareness with the
[normal] judiciary, the
[normal] defence
[normal] and the prosecution 
[normal]to 
[normal]seek to
[normal] minimize the risk of
[normal] further wrongful convictions
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]45
[normal]              
[normal]Nevertheless, w
[normal]e continue to receive applications from people convicted in these circumstances, some quite recently. 
[normal]Between November 2011 and
[normal] November 2013
[normal], we received 
[normal]approximately 80 applications 
[normal]of this type.
[normal] S
[normal]ince our las
[normal]t report to 
[normal]this
[normal] Committee, 
[normal]we have referred 
[normal]f
[normal]ourteen 
[normal]such
[normal] cases
[normal]; 
[normal]twelve 
[normal]convictions have been 
[normal]quashed;
[normal] 
[normal]one
[normal] person abandoned the
[normal]ir
[normal] appeal 
[normal]and one case remains to be heard.
[normal] 
[normal]There is likely to be a significant further stock of such cases 
[normal]from people who are unaware that
[normal] their conviction is unsafe. We are working with Crown Prosecution Service to identify these.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]46
[normal]              
[normal]Another 
[normal]new 
[normal]type of case that concern us are 
[normal]those involving
[normal] victims of human trafficking 
[normal]who may have been compelled to commit 
[normal]the
[normal] crime
[normal] for which they are convicted and, thus, have a defence. Those convicted are often children or young adults. 
[normal]&#xa0;
