[normal]Triennial Review of the Commission[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]48
[normal]              
[normal]During 2012/13 a triennial review of the Commission took place; the final report 
[normal]was
[normal] published 
[normal]in
[normal] June 2013. We are delighted with the positive endorsement of our work and the support for our continued existence. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]49
[normal]              
[normal]The report 
[normal]recommended 
[normal]strengthen
[normal]ing
[normal] the role of Chair and
[normal] changing 
[normal]governance structures.
[normal] 
[normal]There have been preliminary discus
[normal]sions within the Commission and 
[normal]proposals on the role of the Chair are agreed.  As regards governance more generally, it was not considered
[normal] 
[normal]appropriate to 
[normal]reach
[normal] a settled view when the
[normal] MoJ’s
[normal] process to advertise the post of Chair and make an appointment was 
[normal]ongoing
[normal].  The Chair was re-appointed 
[normal]in
[normal] November 2013 and the matter will now be 
[normal]discussed
[normal] at the next Commission Board meeting on 28 January.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]50
[normal]              
[normal]The triennial review reinforces the need for the Commission’s independence and the requirement for a separation of powers between the executive and the judiciary. Whilst that is welcome, the Commission remains concerned about what may be perceived as an erosion of its independence 
[normal]arising from pressures on 
[normal]it
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]on 
[normal]other Arms’ Length Bodies
[normal],
[normal] to 
[normal]conform to centralised control
[normal]s 
[normal]applied
[normal] in way
[normal]s
[normal] that, in our view, fail to give due consideration to 
[normal]the 
[normal]essential differences
[normal] between central government and independen
[normal]t
[normal] public bodies
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]For th
[normal]ose
[normal] reasons, the Commission remains concerned about 
[normal]the loss of 
[normal]its
[normal] 
[normal]own 
[normal]website. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Website and branding [bold]&#xa0;[bold]51
[normal]              
[normal]The Commission was disappointed to have been required by the Government’s 2010 website 
[normal]rationalisation
[normal] programme to close its own dedicated website
[normal]. 
[normal]We pursued every available avenue to oppose the loss of our site
[normal] and made what we considered to be a strong business case based on the 
[normal]premise
[normal] that having our own site was 
[normal]an
[normal] important demonstration of our independence
[normal] 
[normal]and a 
[normal]vital to
[normal]ol for
[normal] 
[normal]e
[normal]nsuring that
[normal] 
[normal]potential 
[normal]applicants
[normal] and other interested parties had reasonable access to us.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]52
[normal]              
[normal]Since 
[normal]2011 we
[normal] have rel
[normal]ied, unhappily, 
[normal]on the justice.gov.uk site.
[normal] 
[normal]It is with considerable trepidation that we 
[normal]face the prospect of the 
[normal]move later this year to the .gov.uk site. We view that as a further step along a road to which we were, 
[normal]as explained
[normal] above, fundamentally opposed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]53
[normal]              
[normal]The nub of this is that potential victims of miscarriages of justice
[normal] often
[normal] see themselves as victi
[normal]ms of the State as prosecutor. 
[normal]To say that to seek redress they can go to a body
[normal] supposedly
[normal] independent of the executive, but one whose website has the word “State” over the doorway, is to risk the appearance of absurdity if not worse.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]54
[normal]              
[normal]There have 
[normal]also been
[normal] moves to 
[normal]rationalise branding for public bodies including NDPBs such as the Commission. This proposal, under which the Commission would 
[normal]be
[normal] required to adopt the same logo and other branding elements as a 
[normal]range
[normal] of other public bodies, caused us considerable concern. Again, we argued that being required to adopt the coat of arms-based branding used by various bodies, including central government departments, would seriously compromise perception of our independence
[normal],
[normal] undermine 
[normal]confidence in 
[normal]us
[normal] and 
[normal]confuse
[normal] actual and potential applicants
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]Towards the end of 2012 we received the welcome news that 
[normal]we will
[normal] be exempted from tho
[normal]se proposals. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stakeholder[bold] Activity[bold]&#xa0;[bold]55
[normal]              
[normal]Our aim has been to promote public understanding of our role and to raise informed awareness about the Commission with specific groups such 
[normal]as
[normal] potential applicants, campaigners, the judiciary and the legal profession.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]56
[normal]              
[normal]The main events of our stakeholder 
[normal]a
[normal]ctivity over the last four years have been the successful stakeholder conferences held in 2010 and 2012. We attracted excellent speakers and panellists and a wide range of attendees to both events
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]57
[normal]              
[normal]We have made specific efforts to engage with innocence projects and other university-based 
[normal]pro bono
[normal] projects interested in 
[normal]wrongful convictions 
[normal]and aiming 
[normal]to make
[normal] applications to the Commission.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]58
[normal]              
[normal]We
[normal] have recently made available an advice 
[normal]line so that 
[normal]pro bono
[normal] units can benefit from advice provided by 
[normal]casework s
[normal]taff. In 2012 we ran our first work experience placements for university students. The principal aim of our engagement with university projects is to encourage them to make timely and good quality applications in relation to appropriate cases.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]59
[normal]              
[normal]In June 2013 we worked wit
[normal]h 
[normal]Warwick
[normal] 
[normal]University
[normal] to provide
[normal] 
[normal]Commission 
[normal]specific training for solicitors and barristers
[normal]. We expect that this will 
[normal]have
[normal] increased understanding of the Commission and helped to improve the quality of applications to us. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Academic research [bold]&#xa0;[bold]60
[normal]              
[normal]The Commission has, 
[normal]with appropriate safeguards in place, allowed controlled access to a number of 
[normal]academic 
[normal]research projects exploring various aspects of 
[normal]our
[normal] work. The research phase of two projects is complete and we expect to see publication of the results in 2014. Two further projects are still in the research phase and another has yet to begin. These projects are in addition to several published 
[normal]works 
[normal]based on access to Commission material.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]IT[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]61
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Until 2012/13 the Commission’s IT service was outsourced to a
[normal] private
[normal] company, but the decision was made to bring the service in-house.  
[normal]We also conducted a
[normal] review of our third party support contracts.  The resultant changes generated substantial savings.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]62
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The Commission has invested 
[normal]in secure remote workin
[normal]g facilities for some Commissioners and staff
[normal]. 
[normal]This has enabled more 
[normal]flexible working and 
[normal]has
[normal], together with 
[normal]some
[normal] 
[normal]“hot-desking”,
[normal] 
[normal]helped
[normal] 
[normal]to accommodate the recent
[normal]ly
[normal] increase
[normal]d
[normal] staff numbers
[normal] in the much smaller premises to which the Commission move
[normal]d
[normal], for financial reasons, in May 2010.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]63
[normal]              
[normal]Other 
[normal]current
[normal] 
[normal]IT 
[normal]projects 
[normal]include the crucial 
[normal]replacement 
[normal]of 
[normal]our ageing and now 
[normal]unsupported case management system
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
